family:Arial,sans-serif; font-size:14px; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:17px; text-decoration:none;" target="_blank">jimadkins (@jimadkins) 分享的帖子</a></p></div></blockquote><p><script async src="//platform.instagram.com/en_US/embeds.js"></script></p><p>和记黄埔的遗产仍然被人们所感受到。 2019 年，乐队发行了<a href="https://www.nme.com/reviews/various-artists-tiny-changes-a-celebration-of-frightened-rabbits-the-midnight-organ-fight-2526196">一张翻唱他们的开创性专辑《The Midnight Organ Fight》的专辑，</a>其中包括<a href="https://www.nme.com/artists/biffy-clyro">Biffy Clyro</a> 、Death Cab For Cutie 的 Ben Gibbard、 <a href="https://www.nme.com/artists/chvrches">Chvrches</a>的 Lauren Mayberry、 <a href="https://www.nme.com/artists/julien-baker">Julien Baker</a> 、 <a href="https://www.nme.com/artists/daughter">Daughter</a> 、Sarah Silverman、The Midnight Organ Fight<a href="https://www.nme.com/artists/the-twilight-sad">等</a>人的翻唱专辑。 <a href="https://www.nme.com/artists/the-twilight-sad">《暮光之城》的悲伤</a>等等 - 全部由斯科特在去世前策划。在他去世后的几年里， <a href="https://www.nme.com/artists/the-national">The National</a>和<a href="https://www.nme.com/artists/frank-turner">Frank Turner</a>等乐队翻唱了《Frightened Rabbit》——后者甚至<a href="https://www.nme.com/news/music/listen-to-frank-turners-moving-tribute-to-scott-hutchison-a-wave-across-a-bay-3136846">创作了关于他已故朋友的单曲《A Wave Across The Bay》</a> 。</p><p> <em>《Living In Color》</em>的目标与此类似，《Heads Roll Off》的歌词与“<em>为地球做出微小的改变</em>”一起成为了 Frightened Rabbit 粉丝的口头禅：“<em>当一切都消失了，有些东西带着它上</em>。”</p><p> “这一直是我做这些甚至成为乐队鼓手的一个重要原因：你希望有人看到你在做什么并决定自己尝试一下，然后意识到这可以是一份工作或职业， ”格兰特说。 “通过他的音乐和歌词，他的贡献很重要。</p><p> “我总是热衷于将他如何启发其他艺术家用不同的媒介进行创作或对现有艺术的不同解释作为这本书的一部分。所有这些纹身背后都有一个故事。歌词“ <em>Something Carry on</em> ”非常适合概括整个事情和想法。成为音乐家并不意味着你不能成为视觉艺术家或舞蹈家。他激励了其他社区的人们，除了他们只是拿起吉他或其他什么东西。”</p><p>戴夫继续说道：“在与斯科特的对话中，一些像十字架这样的图案一开始就被抛弃了，但我只是喜欢粉丝们如何挑选这些东西，并与他们一起寻找斯科特作品的意义。现在它们是乐队和歌迷之间联系的小象征。</p><p> “每个人都把自己的故事带到那个小十字架上。对于很多人来说，这意味着整个世界。当受惊的兔子粉丝看到那个银色的小十字架时，他们几乎不需要说什么。只要彼此稍微看一眼，他们就知道了。它一开始只是一个草图，现在它是如此强大。”</p><p> Just last month, <a href="https://www.nme.com/news/music/watch-sam-fender-cover-frightened-rabbits-the-modern-leper-at-trnsmt-3466963">Sam Fender even performed a cover of the fan favourite &#39;The Modern Leper&#39; during his headline set at Scotland&#39;s TRNSMT Festival</a> – a rendition which Grant described as “amazing” and a sign of the “timeless” nature of Scott&#39;s work.</p><p> “The way that Scott wrote music means that he&#39;ll never be time-stamped as easily as some other writers,” he said. “People are always going to have the thoughts and feeling that he sings about and describes, and hopefully future generations can relate to that.</p><p> “When I heard that Sam Fender was going to cover the song – which was just the morning of the festival – I thought he&#39;d just do a little acoustic thing or he&#39;ll stick a small bit in at the end of another song. But it was proper! It was certainly better than us!</p><p> “He&#39;d clearly put thought and time into it and that shows how much it meant to him, his band and how much he knew it would mean to the crowd in Scotland. Sam&#39;s just amazing.” </p><p><iframe loading="lazy" title="Sam Fender - The Modern Leper (FRabbits cover) with his guitar-tech! TRNSMT 2023" width="696" height="392" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/pY_KcW4qqp0?feature=oembed" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share" allowfullscreen></iframe></p><p> Proceeds from the book once again go towards <a href="https://www.tinychanges.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Tiny Changes</a> – the <a href="https://www.nme.com/news/music/scott-hutchisons-brother-and-bandmate-grant-reflects-on-a-year-of-their-tiny-changes-mental-health-charity-2673994">mental health charity set up by Scott&#39;s family in his memory</a> .</p><p> “When we first started it and were looking at other charities, we realised there was literally nothing for us to reference,” said Grant. “There&#39;s nothing like it, which made us even more determined to make it happen. I still feel the same. There&#39;s nothing on this scale for a young persons&#39; mental health charity with his visual element that&#39;s so strong.</p><p> “It&#39;s been incredible for me to see it flourish, while not being officially involved anymore. The plan was always to set it up and hand it over to someone who knows what they&#39;re doing. They&#39;re doing a great job, and it&#39;s becoming something recognisable. People are going to Tiny Changes not from Frightened Rabbit or Scott&#39;s story, but because they see it as an important charity that&#39;s tackling something huge.”</p><p> As time goes on, the need for Tiny Changes only seems to increase.</p><p> “Every charity&#39;s aim should be to become obsolete – to have an end goal to just one day wind up because they&#39;ve solved the problem,” Grant continued. “Charities involved in social issues are all going in the wrong direction – especially as a portion of society just keep getting battered with one thing after the next. There&#39;s not the support or the advice for those people get access to.</p><p> “With us being a children and young persons&#39; charity, we&#39;ve probably not even seen the full scale of the impact of COVID and the cost of living crisis. It&#39;s not a great time, but seeing Tiny Changes grow and make such an effort to help people is encouraging.” </p><figure id="attachment_2366425" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-2366425" style="width: 2000px" class="wp-caption alignnone"><img decoding="async" loading="lazy" class="wp-image-2366425 size-full" src="https://www.nme.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/GettyImages-520525156_GRANT_SCOTT_HUTCHISON_2000.jpg" alt="" width="2000" height="1270" srcset="https://www.nme.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/GettyImages-520525156_GRANT_SCOTT_HUTCHISON_2000.jpg 2000w, https://www.nme.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/GettyImages-520525156_GRANT_SCOTT_HUTCHISON_2000-696x442.jpg 696w, https://www.nme.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/GettyImages-520525156_GRANT_SCOTT_HUTCHISON_2000-1392x884.jpg 1392w, https://www.nme.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/GettyImages-520525156_GRANT_SCOTT_HUTCHISON_2000-400x254.jpg 400w, https://www.nme.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/GettyImages-520525156_GRANT_SCOTT_HUTCHISON_2000-800x508.jpg 800w, https://www.nme.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/GettyImages-520525156_GRANT_SCOTT_HUTCHISON_2000-1068x678.jpg 1068w" sizes="(max-width: 2000px) 100vw, 2000px" /><figcaption id="caption-attachment-2366425" class="wp-caption-text"> Grant and Scott Hutchison of Frightened Rabbit. Credit: Shirlaine Forrest</figcaption></figure><p> Beyond the new book and charity work, Dave and Grant said that they were planning to further keep Scott&#39;s memory alive by eventually putting on an exhibition of his work. Grant will also be busy this year on the road, having recently <a href="https://www.nme.com/news/music/frightened-rabbit-drummer-and-scott-hutchisons-brother-grant-becomes-full-time-member-of-the-twilight-sad-3318144">joined Frightened Rabbit friends and collaborators The Twilight Sad</a> . Having been <a href="https://www.nme.com/news/music/road-cure-support-band-twilight-sad-share-tour-photo-diary-1911694">hand-picked by frontman Robert Smith</a> , the cult Scottish post-punk band have been supporting <a href="https://www.nme.com/artists/the-cure">The Cure</a> on all world tour dates in recent years, with fans now eagerly awaiting the follow-up to a <a href="https://www.nme.com/reviews/the-twilight-sad-it-won-t-be-like-this-all-the-time-review-2431752">cclaimed 2019 album &#39;It Won/t Be Like This All The Time</a> &#39;.</p><p> “Apparently it&#39;s coming!” said Grant of new material. “We&#39;re playing South America with The Cure at the end of the year, so you&#39;d have to ask James and Andy as they&#39;re the ones that write everything, but that&#39;s the plan. It&#39;s just that Robert Smith took up a lot of our time this year, so we&#39;re probably looking at next year – but that&#39;s the plan.”</p><p> And will be playing on the record?</p><p> “Hopefully! The three tours I&#39;ve done with them has been my interview so hopefully I&#39;ve passed.”</p><p> <em>Living In Colour: The Art Of Scott Hutchison</em> is out now, published by Faber Music. Order it <a href="https://frightenedrabbit.warnerartists.net/gb/frightened-rabbit/living-in-colour-the-art-of-scott-hutchison/9780571542499.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener">here.</a></p><p> The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://www.nme.com/news/music/scott-hutchison-book-living-in-colour-interview-grant-dave-sam-fender-3477826">New Scott Hutchison artwork book shows his “generosity with his creativity”</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://www.nme.com">NME</a> .</p> ;
